    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>When should I refinance my mortgage?</summary>
        <p>Refinancing typically makes sense when current interest rates are at least 0.5 to 1 percentage point lower than your existing rate, you plan to stay in your home long enough to pass the break-even point (where monthly savings exceed closing costs), and your credit and finances qualify you for better terms. Other good reasons include switching from an adjustable-rate to a fixed-rate mortgage, eliminating PMI, or shortening your loan term. Use our <a href="/financial-calculators/refinance-calculator/">refinance calculator</a> to see if the numbers work for your situation.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How much does it cost to refinance?</summary>
        <p>Closing costs for a refinance typically range from 2% to 5% of the loan amount. On a $300,000 mortgage, expect to pay $6,000 to $15,000. These costs include origination fees, appraisal fees, title insurance, attorney fees, and other processing charges. Some lenders offer no-closing-cost refinances, but the costs are typically covered by a higher interest rate, which costs more over the life of the loan. Always compare the total cost, not just the upfront fees.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What credit score do I need to refinance?</summary>
        <p>Most conventional lenders require a minimum credit score of 620 for a refinance, though 740 or higher will get you the best rates. FHA streamline refinances may accept scores as low as 580, and VA refinances often have no formal minimum. The difference between a 660 score and a 760 score can translate to 0.5% or more in interest rate, which on a $300,000 loan means roughly $90 per month in savings. If your score is below 740, consider improving it before applying.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the break-even point for refinancing?</summary>
        <p>The break-even point is the number of months it takes for your monthly savings to equal the total closing costs of the refinance. Calculate it by dividing your total closing costs by your monthly payment savings. For example, $8,000 in closing costs divided by $200 in monthly savings equals 40 months. If you plan to stay in your home longer than 40 months, the refinance saves you money. This is the single most important calculation in any refinancing decision. Our <a href="/financial-calculators/refinance-calculator/">refinance calculator</a> computes this automatically.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can I refinance with negative equity?</summary>
        <p>Refinancing with negative equity (owing more than your home is worth) is challenging but not impossible. Most conventional lenders require at least 3-5% equity, and 20% equity to avoid PMI. However, government programs may help: FHA Streamline Refinances allow refinancing regardless of current home value if you are current on your existing FHA loan, and VA Interest Rate Reduction Refinance Loans (IRRRLs) offer similar flexibility for eligible veterans. If you have negative equity, contact your current loan servicer to discuss what options are available to you.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

